'''Mononobe Shrine''' (もののべじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in {{jalink|Tsutsui (Nagoya)|Q62588744|Tsutsui}}, {{jalink|Higashi-ku (Nagoya)|Q578824|Higashi-ku}}, {{jalink|Nagoya|Q11751}}, {{jalink|Aichi Prefecture|Q80434}}. It has been identified with "Mononobe Shrine" of Aichi District, Owari Province, in the '{{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}},' but as noted below, there are differing views.

=== History ===
It is an old shrine with a tradition of founding in the era of {{jalink|Emperor Suinin|Q314850}}, and is said to have once had broad precinct grounds. With a large stone as {{jalink|shintai|Q327532}}, it was called '''Ishigami-dō''' or '''Yama-no-Kami''' until the {{jalink|Edo period}}. The '{{jalink|Kanbun Muramura Oboegaki|Q137766629}}' compiled around the mid-{{jalink|17th century|Q7016}} records "Furui Village ... Yama-no-Kami," suggesting it was worshiped as a mountain deity at that time. In the {{jalink|Genroku|Q1325001}} era, {{jalink|Tokugawa Tsunashige|Q982743}} is said to have repaired the dilapidated shrine buildings<ref name="立て板"/><ref name="由緒記"/>.

The large stone called "Kaname-ishi," treated as sacred object, is said to be under the shrine building, with a legend that {{jalink|Emperor Jimmu|Q200188}} used it to pacify the {{jalink|land|Q6256}} when subduing this area.

In the Edo period, {{jalink|Amano Nobukage|Q6535030}} identified this shrine as the Owari Aichi District "Mononobe Shrine" listed in the '{{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}},' and this became the prevailing view. However, his basis was only that its deity was {{jalink|Umashimaji|Q10946169|Umashimaji-no-Mikoto}}, ancestral deity of the {{jalink|Mononobe clan|Q1755836}}, and no materials such as {{jalink|munafuda|Q8008834}} survive. Late-Edo local historian {{jalink|Tsuda Masao|Q22123474}} criticized identifying this shrine as Mononobe Shrine and argued the original Mononobe Shrine was {{jalink|Gokiso Hachimangū|Q3109957}}. Archaeologically, few ancient remains are found around this site, whereas around {{jalink|Gokiso|Q50984787}} kofun and abandoned temple sites are scattered; therefore, the theory identifying Mononobe-gō in Aichi District of the '{{jalink|Wamyō Ruijushō|Q2702542}}' with the Gokiso area is considered stronger{{Sfn|名古屋郷土文化会|1986|p=5}}.

In {{jalink|1868|Q7717}} ({{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}} 1), this shrine was formally identified with the Shikinaisha "Mononobe Shrine" and ranked village shrine, but today it is unranked. In {{jalink|1953|Q18585}} ({{jalink|Shōwa|Q327567}} 28), the honden and haiden were built<ref name="由緒記"/>.

