'''Mononobe Shrine''' (もののべじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} in {{ill|lt=Tsutsui (Nagoya)|Q62588744|WD=Q62588744|lt=Tsutsui}}, {{ill|lt=Higashi-ku (Nagoya)|Q578824|WD=Q578824|lt=Higashi-ku}}, {{ill|lt=Nagoya|Q11751|WD=Q11751}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434}}. It has been identified with "Mononobe Shrine" of Aichi District, Owari Province, in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932}},' but as noted below, there are differing views.

=== History ===
It is an old shrine with a tradition of founding in the era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850}}, and is said to have once had broad precinct grounds. With a large stone as {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532}}, it was called '''Ishigami-dō''' or '''Yama-no-Kami''' until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Edo period|1=UNKNOWN|WD=Q184963}}. The '{{ill|lt=Kanbun Muramura Oboegaki|Q137766629|WD=Q137766629}}' compiled around the mid-{{ill|lt=17th century|Q7016|WD=Q7016}} records "Furui Village ... Yama-no-Kami," suggesting it was worshiped as a mountain deity at that time. In the {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001}} era, {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Tsunashige|Q982743|WD=Q982743}} is said to have repaired the dilapidated shrine buildings<ref name="立て板"/><ref name="由緒記"/>.

The large stone called "Kaname-ishi," treated as sacred object, is said to be under the shrine building, with a legend that {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188}} used it to pacify the {{ill|lt=land|Q6256|WD=Q6256}} when subduing this area.

In the Edo period, {{ill|lt=Amano Nobukage|Q6535030|WD=Q6535030}} identified this shrine as the Owari Aichi District "Mononobe Shrine" listed in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932}},' and this became the prevailing view. However, his basis was only that its deity was {{ill|lt=Umashimaji|Q10946169|WD=Q10946169|lt=Umashimaji-no-Mikoto}}, ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Mononobe clan|Q1755836|WD=Q1755836}}, and no materials such as {{ill|lt=munafuda|Q8008834|WD=Q8008834}} survive. Late-Edo local historian {{ill|lt=Tsuda Masao|Q22123474|WD=Q22123474}} criticized identifying this shrine as Mononobe Shrine and argued the original Mononobe Shrine was {{ill|lt=Gokiso Hachimangū|Q3109957|WD=Q3109957}}. Archaeologically, few ancient remains are found around this site, whereas around {{ill|lt=Gokiso|Q50984787|WD=Q50984787}} kofun and abandoned temple sites are scattered; therefore, the theory identifying Mononobe-gō in Aichi District of the '{{ill|lt=Wamyō Ruijushō|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542}}' with the Gokiso area is considered stronger{{Sfn|名古屋郷土文化会|1986|p=5}}.

In {{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|WD=Q7717}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096}} 1), this shrine was formally identified with the Shikinaisha "Mononobe Shrine" and ranked village shrine, but today it is unranked. In {{ill|lt=1953|Q18585|WD=Q18585}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567}} 28), the honden and haiden were built<ref name="由緒記"/>.

