'''Mononobe Shrine''' (もののべじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Tsutsui (Nagoya)|Q62588744|qid=Q62588744|lt=Tsutsui|1=Tsutsui}}, {{ill|lt=Higashi-ku (Nagoya)|Q578824|qid=Q578824|lt=Higashi-ku|1=Higashi-ku, Nagoya}}, {{ill|lt=Nagoya|Q11751|qid=Q11751|1=Nagoya}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It has been identified with "Mononobe Shrine" of Aichi District, Owari Province, in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}},' but as noted below, there are differing views.

=== History ===
It is an old shrine with a tradition of founding in the era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|qid=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}, and is said to have once had broad precinct grounds. With a large stone as {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|qid=Q327532|1=Shintai}}, it was called '''Ishigami-dō''' or '''Yama-no-Kami''' until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period|qid=Q184963}}. The '{{ill|lt=Kanbun Muramura Oboegaki|Q137766629|qid=Q137766629|1=Kanbunmuramuraoboegaki}}' compiled around the mid-{{ill|lt=17th century|Q7016|qid=Q7016|1=17th century}} records "Furui Village ... Yama-no-Kami," suggesting it was worshiped as a mountain deity at that time. In the {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|qid=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} era, {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Tsunashige|Q982743|qid=Q982743|1=Tokugawa Tsunanari}} is said to have repaired the dilapidated shrine buildings<ref name="立て板"/><ref name="由緒記"/>.

The large stone called "Kaname-ishi," treated as sacred object, is said to be under the shrine building, with a legend that {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|qid=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}} used it to pacify the {{ill|lt=land|Q6256|qid=Q6256|1=Country}} when subduing this area.

In the Edo period, {{ill|lt=Amano Nobukage|Q6535030|qid=Q6535030|1=Amano Sadakage}} identified this shrine as the Owari Aichi District "Mononobe Shrine" listed in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}},' and this became the prevailing view. However, his basis was only that its deity was {{ill|lt=Umashimaji|Q10946169|qid=Q10946169|lt=Umashimaji-no-Mikoto|1=Umashimaji}}, ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Mononobe clan|Q1755836|qid=Q1755836|1=Mononobe clan}}, and no materials such as {{ill|lt=munafuda|Q8008834|qid=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}} survive. Late-Edo local historian {{ill|lt=Tsuda Masao|Q22123474|qid=Q22123474|1=Tsuda Masanari}} criticized identifying this shrine as Mononobe Shrine and argued the original Mononobe Shrine was {{ill|lt=Gokiso Hachimangū|Q3109957|qid=Q3109957|1=Gokiso Hachimangū}}. Archaeologically, few ancient remains are found around this site, whereas around {{ill|lt=Gokiso|Q50984787|qid=Q50984787|1=Gokiso}} kofun and abandoned temple sites are scattered; therefore, the theory identifying Mononobe-gō in Aichi District of the '{{ill|lt=Wamyō Ruijushō|Q2702542|qid=Q2702542|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}' with the Gokiso area is considered stronger{{Sfn|名古屋郷土文化会|1986|p=5}}.

In {{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|qid=Q7717|1=1868}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 1), this shrine was formally identified with the Shikinaisha "Mononobe Shrine" and ranked village shrine, but today it is unranked. In {{ill|lt=1953|Q18585|qid=Q18585|1=1953}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 28), the honden and haiden were built<ref name="由緒記"/>.

